In each Roman legion there were six military tribunes, or tribunes οῖ’ the soldiers. Originally they were appointed by the kings, consuls, or dictatore. In the year Rc. 360 the people assumed the right of annually appointing six. But in the year Rc. 310 (at which date four legions were raised year by year), the Lex Atilia was passed, which ordained that sixteen out of the twenty-four tribuneships which were required for the new legions should be at the disposal of the people. In times of great danger to the state all the appointments were usually, however, placed in the hands of the consuls—armis. Abl. dependent on cacata [ξ 119, 1].-e.ruta.
